SIMPLE: lombard
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lombard
<hw>Lom"bard</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or
pertaining to Lombardy, or the inhabitants of Lombardy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lombard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lombard
<hw>Lom"bard</hw>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>lombard</ets>, fr.
the <ets>Longobardi</ets> or <ets>Langobardi</ets>, i. e., Longbeards, a
people of Northern Germany, west of the Elbe, and afterward in Northern
Italy. See <er>Long</er>, and <er>Beard</er>, and cf.
<er>Lumber</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or inhabitant of
Lombardy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A money lender or banker; -- so called because the
business of banking was first carried on in London by
<ets>Lombards</ets>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Lombard-house</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>Lombard</qex> unto this day signifying a bank for usury or
pawns.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A form of cannon formerly in
use.</def> <rj><au>Prescott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lombard Street</b></col>, <cd>the principal street in
London for banks and the offices of note brokers; hence, the money
market and interest of London.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lombardeer</ent>⟦br⟧
